%I A395110 #53 Jul 07 2026 18:22:07
%S A395110 1,2,2,30,122,2264,17991
%N A395110 Number of functions on the grid [0,n+1]^2 which are zero on the boundary and satisfy f(i,j) = ceiling((f(i-1,j)+f(i,j-1)+f(i+1,j)+f(i,j+1))/4) for 1<=i,j<=n.
%C A395110 4*f(i,j) - f(i-1,j) - f(i,j-1) - f(i+1,j) - f(i,j+1) is a Laplacian of the lattice function.
%C A395110 a(n) counts the number of integer superharmonic functions on the grid [1,n]^2 which are 0 on the boundary of [0,n+1]^2 and whose Laplacian takes one of the values {0,1,2,3} in [1,n]^2 (since the sum of all Laplacians is 0, negative values accumulate on the boundary of [0,n+1]^2).
%C A395110 If Laplacian is bounded by 1, and f is 0 on the boundary, the only such function is 0.
%C A395110 If Laplacian is bounded by 2, and f is 0 on the boundary, one can construct 2^(floor(n/2)) different examples of such functions. All of them have a dihedral symmetry. Conjecturally, this is the exact number of such functions.
%C A395110 In dimension 1, number of functions defined on [0,n+1] and satisfying f(0) = f(n+1) = 0, f(i) = ceiling((f(i-1)+f(i+1))/2) is exactly A000016(n+1).
%H A395110 L. Levine, W. Pegden, and Ch. K. Smart, <a href="https://doi.org/10.4007/annals.2017.186.1.1">The Apollonian structure of integer superharmonic matrices</a>, Annals of Mathematics(2) 186(1): 1-67 (July 2017).
%e A395110 For n=3, a(3)=2 since there are two such functions (only the inner 3 X 3 square is shown)
%e A395110   000
%e A395110   000
%e A395110   000,
%e A395110  and
%e A395110   111
%e A395110   111
%e A395110   111.
